        <p class="metadata">Posted by Bill Karwin (bkarwin) on 2007-04-13T17:07:41.000+0000</p> 
        <div class="body">
            <p>For what it's worth, the phpdoc manual says that it's okay to list multiple types together in the @param and @return tags, separated by the pip symbol (|).</p>

<p><a href="http://manual.phpdoc.org/HTMLframesConverter/earthli/phpDocumentor/tutorial_tags.return.pkg.html">http://manual.phpdoc.org/HTMLframesConverter/â€¦</a></p>

<p>There is also an instance in the documentation above of a list containing a class name and 'false' which is a value, not a type name:</p>

<pre class="highlight"><code>
/**
 * example of using @return with a class name
 * @param integer even or odd integer
 * @return Parser|false phpDocumentor Parser object or error
 */
</code></pre>

<p>So phpdoc clearly permits (and even encourages) some forms that PDT doesn't understand.</p>

<p>Should we therefore use 'mixed' whenever we have these cases, and then list the possible types and values in the following text, for example:</p>

<pre class="highlight"><code>
* @return mixed Zend_Db_Table_Row_Abstract or null; the row results per the
*     Zend_Db_Adapter fetch mode, or null if no row found.
</code></pre>

<p>In the example above, the PDT won't parse Zend_Db_Table_Row_Abstract at all, it'll just know 'mixed' as the return type in cases like this.</p>

